By Week 26, the pattern of Trump\'92s second term had settled into something both familiar and more deeply rooted. Power was no longer only seized in bursts of spectacle; it was being wired into the state\'92s plumbing. Immigration enforcement, civil service rules, and the information system itself were used as levers to sort who counted and who did not. The week\'92s events showed a government that still held elections, still answered lawsuits, still convened hearings, yet increasingly treated law, data, and public services as tools for a narrow project rather than as shared goods. The surface remained noisy and fragmented. Underneath, the direction of travel was steady.\
\
On the Democracy Clock, the time at the start of Week 26 was 7:52 p.m., and it remained there at the end. The net change was zero minutes. That stillness did not mean nothing happened. It meant that the week\'92s heavy movement was lateral rather than vertical: traits that were already elevated\'97executive power without oversight, law as weapon, surveillance of citizens, stratified citizenship, crony capitalism\'97grew denser and more entangled, but without a single, sharp break that forced the hands forward. Courts still issued some restraining orders. Congress still held hearings and, in a few cases, pushed back. Civil society still organized. The system\'92s remaining checks did not reverse the drift, but they kept it from tipping into a new, more dangerous phase.\
\
The first major development was the deepening of executive control over the machinery of the state, especially where life and death were at stake. Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem\'92s decree that any FEMA expenditure or contract over $100,000 required her personal approval turned disaster response into a bottleneck at the top. At the same time, the administration had already cut FEMA grants and allowed staff and leadership to erode. A separate decision not to renew call-center contracts after the Texas floods caused answered calls to collapse from more than 3,000 in a day to under 900. These were not just budget choices. They shifted who could get help, and how fast, from a rules-based system to one that depended on the favor and priorities of a small circle. Federal power over floods, fires, and storms became more discretionary.\
\
The same pattern appeared abroad. The State Department ordered the destruction of nearly 500 metric tons of high-nutrition biscuits meant for children in Afghanistan and Pakistan, food that had been bought with U.S. funds and stored after cuts to USAID. The stated rationale was fear that aid might benefit terrorists. The effect was to burn food rather than feed children in a region where the United States had long claimed a humanitarian role. In parallel, the administration dismantled much of the U.S. Agency for Global Media and pushed a rescissions package that cut billions from foreign aid. These moves shrank the tools through which the United States had projected democratic values and soft power, while leaving intact and even expanding the coercive arms of the state.\
\
At home, the most far-reaching structural change came with the creation and implementation of Schedule G in the federal civil service. Trump\'92s executive order, formalized again this week in public reporting, carved out a new category of \'93policy-making or policy-advocating\'94 positions that could be filled and emptied at will. The order was framed as a way to improve operations at the Department of Veterans Affairs, but its reach extended across agencies. It sat alongside mass layoffs at the State Department, including the closure of the Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor, and a Supreme Court stay that allowed the Education Department to proceed with firing nearly half its workforce despite statutory protections. Together, these steps moved the civil service away from neutral expertise and toward a corps of politically dependent functionaries.\
\
The Veterans Affairs system became a test case for how this politicized state would treat vulnerable citizens. In one week, VA leadership banned LGBTQ+ pride flags from hospitals, shut down an office investigating why Black veterans\'92 mental health disability claims were more likely to be rejected, ended gender-affirming care for transgender veterans under a Trump order, and stripped hospital bylaws of explicit protections against discrimination based on marital status or political views. These were not symbolic gestures alone. They altered who could safely seek care, which grievances would be studied, and which identities would be treated as legitimate. Veterans who had already paid the highest price for the country now faced a system that sorted them by identity and ideology.\
\
If the civil service was being reshaped from within, the justice system was being bent from above. Attorney General Pam Bondi fired Joseph Tirrell, the head of the Justice Department\'92s ethics office, without explanation, and then removed more than twenty other DOJ employees tied to investigations of Trump. In the same span, nearly two-thirds of the lawyers in the DOJ unit tasked with defending Trump administration policies resigned, many unwilling to participate in what they saw as efforts to dismantle constitutional governance. The firing of Maurene Comey, a career prosecutor who had handled the Epstein and Ghislaine Maxwell cases and other high-profile matters, underscored the message: those who had pursued powerful figures, or whose names were linked to past checks on Trump, were no longer welcome.\
\
Judicial appointments and emergency rulings reinforced this tilt. The Supreme Court granted an emergency stay that allowed the Education Department to proceed with layoffs of roughly 1,378 employees, despite a lower court\'92s order to reinstate them. The decision expanded presidential leeway to ignore congressional intent on staffing. In Florida, the state supreme court upheld a congressional map that dismantled a Black-influence district and split it into four majority-white districts, rejecting arguments under the state\'92s Fair Districts Amendment. In Washington, Republican senators advanced Emil Bove\'92s nomination to a federal appeals court despite a Democratic walkout and whistleblower allegations that he had urged ignoring court orders. And when a judicial panel blocked John Sarcone III from serving as interim U.S. attorney, the Justice Department simply appointed him \'93special attorney to the attorney general\'94 with the same powers and no time limit, sidestepping the usual confirmation process.\
