Nowhere was the fusion of law and force more visible than in immigration. Early in the week, Trump authorized ICE agents to use \'93whatever means\'94 necessary to protect themselves and ordered the arrest of protesters who impeded raids. ICE Director Todd Lyons issued a memo allowing rapid deportations to third countries with as little as six hours\'92 notice, even without firm assurances against persecution. A broader policy shift made undocumented immigrants ineligible for bond hearings while their deportation cases were pending, moving release decisions from judges to DHS officials. These changes came on top of a massive expansion of ICE officers and detention facilities, funded by a $45 billion allocation over four years, and the use of Title 42 and other tools to turn back asylum seekers.\
\
On the ground, these policies translated into scenes that blurred the line between law enforcement and intimidation. In Southern California, ICE raids at licensed cannabis farms used less-lethal ammunition and tear gas, injuring workers and protesters. One worker, Jaime Alan\'eds, died after falling from a greenhouse roof while trying to hide. Hundreds were arrested. On Terminal Island in Los Angeles, a site once used to incarcerate Japanese Americans, ICE staged workplace sweeps that detained nearly 2,800 people in six weeks. In Oregon, agents broke a car window to arrest Mahdi Khanbabazadeh, an Iranian chiropractor married to a U.S. citizen, as he dropped his child at preschool. In another case, an Irish tourist who overstayed his visa by three days due to a medical issue was held for about 100 days in various detention facilities, including a federal prison, before being deported and banned for a decade.\
\
Detention conditions and targeting patterns revealed a system that treated certain people as outside the circle of rights. At the Alligator Alcatraz facility in Florida, more than 250 detainees had no criminal record, despite official claims that it housed the \'93worst of the worst.\'94 Lawmakers who toured a new ICE center in the Everglades reported 32 people per cage and inadequate sanitation. A Miami Herald report and congressional visits described overcrowding and filth. At the same time, the Justice Department appealed a ruling that barred DHS from arresting people based on racial profiling factors, and the administration fired immigration judges even as Congress had funded more positions. The legal architecture of due process was being hollowed out, while the physical architecture of detention expanded.\
\
Data systems that had been built for service and safety were repurposed for control. ProPublica reported that the IRS was developing a system to share confidential tax data, including home addresses, with ICE for deportation targeting, after an earlier acting general counsel had refused a similar request. Separate reporting showed that the administration had agreed to give ICE access to Medicaid data on 79 million recipients, including addresses and Social Security numbers, over the objections of career staff who warned of statutory violations. These moves, combined with the $6 billion expansion of border surveillance technology funded by Trump\'92s tax bill\'97biometric towers, license plate readers, phone hacking, and social media monitoring\'97created a dense web of state and private systems aimed at tracking a disfavored population.\
