While ordinary people were made more visible to the state, the actions of elites grew more opaque. The Department of Justice and FBI issued a memo concluding that Jeffrey Epstein had died by suicide and that no incriminating client list existed, and announced that no further disclosures would be made. The memo acknowledged more than 300 gigabytes of seized data, including child sexual abuse material, but insisted there was no basis for public release. House Republicans on the Rules Committee twice blocked Democratic amendments that would have forced the DOJ to release the Epstein files within 30 days. A rescissions vote in the House, delayed by controversy over the files, ultimately went forward without new transparency requirements. At the same time, Attorney General Bondi dropped charges against a Utah doctor accused of destroying COVID vaccines and issuing fake vaccination cards, mid-trial, in a move critics saw as politically aligned with anti-vaccine sentiment.\
