The Epstein saga became a prism for the week\'92s information politics. Trump defended Bondi on social media, dismissed questions about Epstein as \'93boring,\'94 and then, under pressure from his own base and figures like Elon Musk, ordered Bondi to release grand jury testimony. The DOJ filed motions to unseal transcripts with redactions, even as it fired Maurene Comey and other prosecutors linked to the case. Speaker Mike Johnson called publicly for the files to be released while having voted to block related amendments. MAGA influencers and Mike Flynn accused the administration of betraying promises to expose elite abusers and called for Bondi\'92s ouster. Wired reported that nearly three minutes were missing from the \'93full raw\'94 surveillance video of Epstein\'92s cell. Senator Dick Durbin demanded information on why 1,000 FBI agents had been assigned to the case. The result was not clarity but layered confusion: partial disclosures, missing footage, firings, lawsuits, and cross-accusations that left the public with more questions than answers.\
\
Beyond Epstein, the information environment was narrowed in quieter ways. NASA announced it would not publish major climate change assessments on its website, despite earlier commitments. The Bureau of Labor Statistics, after budget cuts, now had to estimate 35% of price data, up from 9%, undermining the reliability of inflation figures at the very moment tariffs were driving consumer prices higher. The Commerce Department halted work on a NOAA tool to predict extreme rainfall, weakening the country\'92s ability to plan for climate-driven floods. The administration dismantled most of the U.S. Agency for Global Media, cutting off a long-standing channel for U.S.-backed journalism abroad. Congress, at Trump\'92s urging, passed a $9 billion rescissions package that stripped $1.1 billion from the Corporation for Public Broadcasting and billions more from foreign aid, even as the administration sued members of the CPB board after attempts to fire them.\
\
Media and speech were also pressured through litigation and funding threats. Trump filed a libel and slander suit seeking at least $10 billion against Rupert Murdoch, the Wall Street Journal, and its reporters over a story about a \'93bawdy\'94 letter to Epstein. He also sued Dow Jones and News Corp in a separate action. In response to the same reporting, Representative Randy Fine announced plans to introduce legislation ending the House\'92s subscription contract with the Wall Street Journal. On the other side of the aisle, Governor Gavin Newsom filed a $787 million defamation suit against Fox News and Jesse Watters over a false claim about a phone call with Trump, despite an on-air apology. These suits, from both parties, used the civil courts as battlegrounds with news organizations. Meanwhile, CBS announced it would cancel The Late Show with Stephen Colbert in 2026, citing financial reasons, removing a prominent platform for political satire.\
