Elections and representation were reshaped in ways that were legal on their face but corrosive in effect. In Texas, under Trump\'92s direction, Republicans convened a special session to redraw the congressional map and gain up to five additional red seats, in a state where non-white populations were growing fastest. Attorney General Ken Paxton threatened to arrest Democratic legislators who boycotted the session to deny a quorum. In Florida, the supreme court\'92s approval of a map that dismantled a Black-influence district signaled judicial tolerance for aggressive partisan gerrymanders. In North Carolina, a Republican-majority elections board voted to require voters to provide additional registration information or risk being forced into provisional ballots that might not be counted, a change that could purge nearly 100,000 voters. The Justice Department requested voter rolls from nine states to assemble election data and examine equipment, raising concerns about how such centralized information might be used.\
\
There were pockets of resistance and repair. A federal appeals court temporarily blocked the administration from ending Temporary Protected Status for nearly 12,000 Afghans. Another judge halted the use of a presidential proclamation to ban 80 vetted refugees from entering the United States. A separate court granted a temporary restraining order to keep an Ohio imam, Ayman Soliman, from being transferred out of state before his bond hearing. In Louisiana, a lookback law allowing clergy abuse victims to sue regardless of when the abuse occurred survived a church challenge, and the New Orleans archdiocese filed a settlement plan that included a partial public archive of abuse files. In Congress, the House Armed Services Committee, including some Republicans, voted to block Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth from renaming army bases after Confederate figures, rebuking an executive effort to reverse earlier de-Confederation.\
