Looking ahead from Week 26, several processes were already in motion. The federal trial over North Carolina\'92s redistricting maps was underway, with final submissions due in early August and a decision to follow. The class-action lawsuit challenging courthouse arrests by DHS and DOJ would test the legality of immigration enforcement tactics that blurred the line between court and jail. A coalition of twenty states had sued over FEMA grant cuts, seeking to restore resilience funding. The DOJ\'92s motion to unseal Epstein grand jury transcripts, if granted, could shift the balance between secrecy and disclosure in that case, even as the firings and lawsuits around it continued. Congress had approved the rescissions package; only the president\'92s signature remained before the cuts to public broadcasting and foreign aid became law.\
\
In the larger arc of the term, Week 26 mattered less for a single shock than for the way many strands tightened at once. Executive power over disaster relief, immigration, and the civil service grew more personal and less constrained. Law enforcement and data systems were turned inward on immigrants, Medicaid recipients, and taxpayers, while the crimes and finances of elites were shielded by secrecy, selective prosecution, and libel suits. Public media and scientific data were thinned out, even as disinformation and chaos around the Epstein files and tariffs filled the space. Voting rules and maps in key states were adjusted in ways that favored the ruling coalition and weakened minority representation. Yet courts still issued some stays, Congress still produced occasional bipartisan checks, and cities and citizens still built alternative forms of safety and solidarity.\
\
